<paragraph blockId="144.[151,1437,1797,2041]" box="[151,907,1797,1824]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,262,1797,1824]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Material.</emphasis>
A single nearly complete external mould, 
<collectionCode box="[737,823,1798,1824]" country="Denmark" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/c1ae-v64p" name="Museum Geologicum Universitatis Hafniensis" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">MGUH</collectionCode>
33272.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="144.[151,1437,1797,2041]" box="[199,1010,1833,1861]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,346,1833,1860]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Occurrence.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Limestone Member" authorityName="Gilleaudeau et al." authorityYear="2018" box="[353,693,1834,1860]" class="Gastropoda" family="Cerithiidae" genus="Cerithium" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Cerithium Limestone Member</taxonomicName>
at Skeldervig, Stevns Klint.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="144.[151,1437,1797,2041]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1869,1896]" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Description.</emphasis>
Protoconch high conical with around 3 ¼ to 3 ½ weakly to moderately convex and smooth whorls. Protoconch 
<quantity box="[286,372,1906,1933]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
wide and 
<quantity box="[487,587,1905,1933]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.65">0.65 mm</quantity>
high.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="144.[151,1437,1797,2041]" lastBlockId="145.[151,1437,153,647]" lastPageId="145" lastPageNumber="146" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Teleoconch slender, high-spired, with moderately convex and thin-shelled whorls having a width corresponding to twice the height. Suture deep. Last whorl with gradual transition to convex base and moderately short canal. Aperture relatively short and narrow, the height taking up 36 % of the shell height, and with a width corresponding to 30 % of the height. Columella long, slightly curved and smooth, lacking columellar folds. Siphonal canal moderately wide and deep, not terminating in a notch.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Teleoconch sculpture reticulate with moderately strong spiral and transverse ribs forming tubercles at nodes. First teleoconch whorl only with opisthocyrt and somewhat opisthocline transverse ribs, the number amounting to about 24 per whorl. Following whorl with three and later five spiral ribs in addition to and nearly as strong as transverse ribs. Spiral ribs numbering 15 on last whorl. Transverse ribs die out on adapical part of base.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,382,369,395]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Measurements.</emphasis>
<collectionCode box="[388,474,369,395]" country="Denmark" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/c1ae-v64p" name="Museum Geologicum Universitatis Hafniensis" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">MGUH</collectionCode>
33272 is 
<quantity box="[582,668,368,395]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
high and 
<quantity box="[777,863,369,395]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
wide, consisting of protoconch and 4 ½ teleoconch whorls.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="145.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,441,467]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Remarks.</emphasis>
The specimen corresponds well with the diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Conrad" authorityYear="1860" box="[1061,1128,441,467]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ptychatractidae" genus="Exilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1061,1128,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Exilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but for the short aperture, which takes up much less than half the shell height. Even so it is clear that it is closely related to species like the slightly younger 
<taxonomicName authority="(von Koenen, 1885)" authorityName="von Koenen" authorityYear="1885" baseAuthorityName="von Koenen" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[347,786,512,539]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ptychatractidae" genus="Exilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crassistria">
<emphasis box="[347,542,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Exilia crassistria</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="von Koenen, A." box="[560,777,512,539]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" pagination="1 - 128" refId="ref143230" refString="von Koenen, A. (1885) Ueber eine Paleocane Fauna von Kopenhagen. Abhandlungen der Koniglichen Gesellschaft der Wissenschaften zu Gottingen, 32, 1 - 128, pls. 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1885">von Koenen, 1885</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore it is assigned to this genus. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Conrad" authorityYear="1860" box="[1245,1312,513,539]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ptychatractidae" genus="Exilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1245,1312,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Exilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. differs from the Palaeocene 
<taxonomicName authority="(von Koenen, 1885)" authorityName="von Koenen" authorityYear="1885" baseAuthorityName="von Koenen" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[387,767,548,575]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ptychatractidae" genus="Exilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crassistria">
<emphasis box="[387,536,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">E. crassistria</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="von Koenen, A." box="[551,759,548,575]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" pagination="1 - 128" refId="ref143230" refString="von Koenen, A. (1885) Ueber eine Paleocane Fauna von Kopenhagen. Abhandlungen der Koniglichen Gesellschaft der Wissenschaften zu Gottingen, 32, 1 - 128, pls. 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1885">von Koenen, 1885</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[836,940,549,575]" name="Denmark" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Denmark</collectingCountry>
by the coarser sculpture and slightly shorter aperture. It resembles the Selandian 
<taxonomicName authority="Ravn, 1939" authorityName="Ravn" authorityYear="1939" box="[562,1054,585,611]" class="Gastropoda" family="Buccinidae" genus="Parvisipho" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="crispatus" subGenus="Andonia">
<emphasis box="[562,685,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Parvisipho</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[702,797,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Andonia</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[814,917,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">crispatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ravn, J. P. J." box="[924,1054,585,611]" pageId="145" pageNumber="146" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref138409" refString="Ravn, J. P. J. (1939) Etudes sur les mollusques du Paleocene de Copenhague. Det Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskab. Biologiske Skrifter, 1 (1), 1 - 106 pp., pls. 1 - 4." type="book chapter" year="1939">Ravn, 1939</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1124,1231,585,611]" name="Denmark" pageId="145" pageNumber="146">Denmark</collectingCountry>
, but differs by the relatively higher protoconch and the higher number of transverse ribs.
</paragraph>
